Task 1: Introducing LAN Topologies
Q: What does LAN stand for?
By reading the article provided in this task I have learned about LAN topology such as Star Topology, Bus Topology, Ring Topology and Switch, Router etc.
A: Local Area Network

Q: What is the verb given to the job that Routers perform?
It’s a router’s job to connect networks and pass data between them. It does this by using routing (hence the name router!).
Routing is the label given to the process of data travelling across networks. Routing involves creating a path between networks so that this data can be successfully delivered.
A: Routing

Q: What device is used to centrally connect multiple devices on the local network and transmit data to the correct location?
From the article given on this task I have learned that Switches are dedicated devices within a network that are designed to aggregate multiple other devices. 
Switches keep track of what device is connected to which port. This way, when they receive a packet, instead of repeating that packet to every port like a hub would do, it just sends it to the intended target, thus reducing network traffic.
A: Switch

Q: What topology is cost-efficient to set up?
Bus topologies are one of the easier and more cost-efficient topologies to set up because of their expenses, such as cabling or dedicated networking equipment used to connect these devices.
A: Bus Topology

Q: What topology is expensive to set up and maintain?
From the article on this task I learned that because more cabling and the purchase of dedicated networking equipment is required for Star topology, it is more expensive than any of the other topologies.
A: Star Topology

